mann</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=G0300662"><gtr:id>76765A6B-1429-4098-A91F-E049433E70E1</gtr:id><gtr:title>Genome Damage and Stability Centre</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G0300662</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Our genomes are made up of long DNA molecules that contain the genetic blueprint that tells every part of our body how to function. This vast reference library, which contains all the instructions that both allowed us to grow from an egg to an adult and dictates every function of our everyday lives is continually being damaged. One example is our skin cells. The genome in these cells is constantly damaged by sunlight. Another is our intestines: our intestinal cells? genomes are damaged by carcinogens in food. In all our cells, simply by existing at body temperature, our genomes are constantly being damaged, at the rate of 1000 bases (the building blocks of our genomes) every hour in every cell. Fortunately our cells contain sophisticated mechanisms for protecting our genomes by repairing all this damage. It is these protection processes that are the focus of the work of the Genome Damage and Stability Centre. 
If these repair mechanisms stop working, properly, there are two possible consequences. First, genetic damage (ie wrong instructions) can be passed on to our offspring. This could cause a genetic disease. Second, individual cells in our body can start losing information and accumulating permanent genetic changes (mutations). When this happens, cancer can result.
The Centre will enable scientists of different disciplines to work together and benefit from each other?s expertise. Our work will range from studies on the protein molecules that repair DNA inside cells, the genes that are altered in cancer cells through to investigations on cancer-prone people. Part of our research is the study of several genetic diseases in which one of the DNA repair systems is faulty. This results in the affected individuals having very high incidences of cancer, more than 1000 times higher than in the general population. By discovering the nature of the defects in people with these disorders, we are able not only to help diagnose and hopefully cure these conditions, but also to gain general insights into how cancers can arise. This will help ultimately to design more rational cancer therapies.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>DNA damage response (DDR) pathways maintain the stability of the genome to ensure its accurate duplication and equal chromosome segregation. The goal of the Genome Damage and Stability Centre is to understand the basic biology of these pathways and their relationship to human disease. The development of the GDSC was initiated in October 2001 when the MRC Cell Mutation Unit closed following the retirement of the Director, Professor Bryn Bridges. In the past two years the GDSC has moved into new premises and established a group of leading scientists in the field of DNA damage responses. We have produced an internationally competitive body of work, established an effective multi-disciplinary research environment, built a complementary group of research laboratories, established a successful infrastructure (and corresponding managerial structure) and facilitated collaborations between Centre scientists. This application is for Centre status and resources to allow us to maintain excellence in research and to extend our research into new areas. We intend to achieve this by: 1. Establishing structural studies as a common tool within the programs of the Centre. 2. Establishing a physical and technical infrastructure to exploit mouse model systems within the programs of the Centre. 3. Maintaining and promoting collaborations within the Centre and with the School of Life Sciences (LifeSci), a key to expanding multidisciplinarity. 4 Continuing to develop central infrastructure for cost-effective and accessible use of complex technology. 
Particular emphasis is placed on building a skill base within the GDSC and on the interaction with LifeSci.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>2141794</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Work Experience</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an open day or visit at my research institution</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>2B5B070D-7D89-46D1-BF45-7ADFF3AB33B3</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Orgainise 1 week lab experience for 4-6 students, participants labs from across the Centre

